04725nam a22007095i 9783110731927DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107319277 a10.1515/97831107319272doi  a(DE-B1597)574100  a(OCoLC)1380731341  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aHIS0000002bisacsh1 aKleemann, Katrin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Mist Connection :bAn Environmental History of the Laki Eruption of 1783 and Its Legacy /cKatrin Kleemann. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4cÂ©2023  a1 online resource (XIII, 387 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistorical Catastrophe Studies / Historische Katastrophenforschung ,x2699-722300tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- t1 Introduction: 1783 - A Year of Wonders -- t2 A Volcano Comes to Life -- t3 Shaking the World -- t4 The Mystery Remains -- t5 Conclusions: A Modern Perspective on the Laki Eruption -- tIllustrations -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aIn the summer of 1783, an unusual dry fog descended upon large parts of the northern hemisphere. The fog brought with it bloodred sunsets, a foul sulfuric odor, and a host of other peculiar weather events. Inspired by the Enlightenment, many naturalists attempted to find reasonable explanations for these occurrences. Between 8 June 1783 and 7 February 1784, a 27-kilometer-long fissure volcano erupted in the Icelandic highlands. It produced the largest volume of lava released by any volcanic eruption on planet Earth in the last millennium. In Iceland, the eruption led to the death of one-fifth of the population. The jetstream carried its volcanic gases further afield to Europe and beyond, where they settled as a fog, the origin of which puzzled naturalists and laypersons. "A Mist Connection" is an environmental history that documents the Laki eruption and its consequences for Iceland and the wider world. The book combines methods of historical disaster research, climate history, global history, history of science, and geology in an interdisciplinary approach. Icelandic flood lava eruptions of this scale have a statistical recurrence period of 200 to 500 years; it is crucial to understand their nature so that we can prepare for the next one. An eruption of this magnitude would surely be disastrous for our modern, globalized, and interconnected world.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4a18th century. 4aEnvironmental History. 4aLaki Eruption. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aGeology.  aIceland.  aVolcano.  aWeather.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z978311117578208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishz978311131913108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2023z9783111318189oZDB-23-DEG0 cEPUBz97831107320230 cprintz978311073717240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110731927zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110731927zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110731927/original  a978-3-11-117578-2 DG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1b2023  a978-3-11-131913-1 EBOOK PACKAGE History 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2 EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2023